            During economic downturns, Harvard's endowment – 70%+ in illiquid alternative investments – cannot be rapidly deployed for operating needs. Federal grants freeze. Corporate sponsorships pause. The institution's most reliable crisis-period resource is often its least mapped: donors holding liquid assets in Donor Advised Funds, marketable securities, or money-market positions who are willing to accelerate or redirect existing philanthropic intent. The Shadow Endowment Strategy maps the pipeline by <em>liquidity tier</em> rather than gift stage alone, enabling the President and AVP to identify which relationships can produce immediate cash-equivalent gifts within 30–90 days of a market disruption event.
          </p>

          <!-- Pipeline liquidity breakdown -->
<h4 style="font-size:.85rem;margin-bottom:14px">Pipeline Liquidity Tier Analysis – FY2026 Principal Gift Pool ($2.8B)</h4>
<div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-bottom:14px"><h4>How to read this</h4><p>Tier 1 and Tier 2 are near-term liquidity sources. Tier 3 is not a cash reserve; it is a long-horizon cultivation pool that should remain in stewardship until a liquidity event, estate plan, or asset conversion creates readiness.</p></div>
